'''Vidant Medical Transport (Previously, EastCare)''' is the [[Intensive-care medicine|critical care]] mobile [[Air ambulance|air]] and [[Ambulance|ground]] transport of [[Vidant Health]] (VH) at [[Vidant Medical Center]] (VMC).  It serves 29 counties in [[Eastern North Carolina]] and extends into [[Virginia]].<ref name="The Siren">{{Cite news| last = Ferguson| first = Jeffrey| coauthors =| title = What’s Going on at EastCare?| newspaper = The Siren| location = Greenville, North Carolina| pages = 1–2| language =| publisher = ECU Emergency Medicine – Brody School of Medicine at East Carolina University| date = October – December 2008| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-dhs/ecuem/upload/The-Siren-Oct_Dec_08_2.pdf| accessdate = October 12, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=EastCare Air Medical Service takes dlivery of EC135, with two EC145s to follow|url=http://www.helihub.com/2010/01/29/eastcare-air-medical-service-takes-dlivery-of-ec135-with-two-ec145s-to-follow/|accessdate=24 July 2011}}</ref>   It is sponsored by VMC and [[The Brody School of Medicine at East Carolina University|The Brody School of Medicine]] at [[East Carolina University]].  VMC is the only [[Trauma center|level 1 trauma center]] east of [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]].<ref>{{cite web| last = Office of Emergency Medical Services| title = Designated Trauma Centers| work = NC Division of Health Service Regulation| publisher = North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services| date = March 15, 2010| url = http://www.ncdhhs.gov/dhsr/EMS/trauma/traumacenter.html| accessdate = October 13, 2010}}</ref>  It is one of nine air ambulances plus [[Marine Corps Air Station Cherry Point]], located in North Carolina, and serves a [[radius]] of {{convert|230|nmi}} around [[Greenville, North Carolina|Greenville]] without refueling.<ref name="Dial Codes">{{Cite book| title = Dial Codes| publisher = North Carolina Office of Emergency Medical Services| date = October 22, 2010| location = Raleigh, North Carolina| pages = 139–142| url = http://www.ncdhhs.gov/dhsr/EMS/pdf/dialcode.pdf}}</ref>  Jeffrey D. Ferguson is the current Medical Director for Vidant Medical Transport and Michele Kuszajewski is the Program Director.<ref name="Dial Codes"/><ref>{{cite web   | title = Full-Time Emergency Medicine Faculty   | work = ECU Emergency Medicine   | publisher = The Brody School of Medicine   | date = February 11, 2009  | url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-dhs/ecuem/fac/Full-Time-Faculty2.cfm | accessdate = October 12, 2010}}</ref>

Vidant Medical Transport can be dispatched for a number of causes, including: [[Trauma (medicine)|trauma]], [[burn]], [[infant|neonatal]], high risk [[pregnancy]], [[hyperbaric medicine]], [[stroke]] and [[myocardial infarction]].<ref>{{cite web   | last = Dale-Reeder | first = Rhonda | title = Critical Lessons Learned from Trauma   | work =    | publisher = University Health Systems of Eastern Carolina   | url = http://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:L4ENFskolp0J:www.race-er.com/assets/PDFs/emsTransportMeeting1/STEMI%2520Trauma_Reeder.pdf+eastcare&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESgYSOZmRAkNFjMcZ5OsNJlgkKL4NQvAACDc4c6pbdMlrK0bv-mR1rl_5XByLmp5zP7W6tVNF3rC3zhQPxMN_6Kqpk4X2iX789tZzIy2Uwpkk5pNFxWbVi5BP4NeZ8KKqx586dD2&sig=AHIEtbRidvsQObKV6xlHk_0U5tfNOgF7qw   | format = powerpoint   | accessdate = October 13, 2010}}</ref>  Vidant Medical Transport is most often sent for [[Heart disease|cardiac patients]], followed by trauma, [[pediatrics|pediatric]] and neonatal patients.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Abramowitz|first=Michael   | title = EastCare celebrates 25 years   | newspaper = The Daily Reflector   | publisher = The Daily Reflector   | date = October 20, 2010   | url = http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:ad4SwU_drXIJ:www.reflector.com/news/eastcare-celebrates-25-years-154260+http://www.reflector.com/news/eastcare-celebrates-25-years-154260&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us   | accessdate = October 20, 2010}}</ref>  The only air crash occurred on January 8, 1987 when everyone on board perished.

In January 2012, Vidant Medical Transport changed its name from EastCare as part of a system wide renaming initiative.

==History==
On December 18, 1984, the VMC Board of Trustees budgeted $754,119 to set up a [[helicopter]] ambulance service.<ref name="PCMH"/>  It was established by VMC on April 8, 1985.<ref>{{cite web   | title = EastCare   | work = Emergency Medical Services   | publisher = Pitt County Development Commission   | year = 2010   | url = http://locateincarolina.com/protective-services/emergency-medical-services/   | accessdate = October 12, 2010}}</ref>  On June 30, 1985, an open house was held to usher in the new ambulance service.<ref name="PCMH"/>

